==Game notes== ===Northeastern=== {{Linescore Amfootball| |Road=Huskies |R1=0 |R2=7 |R3=0 |R4=7 |Home='''Cardinals''' |H1=7 |H2=24 |H3=7 |H4=10 }}
Nate Davis passed for 280&nbsp;yards and three touchdowns as Ball State beat Northeastern 48â14&nbsp;in the season opener for both teams. MiQuale Lewis had 11&nbsp;carries for 95&nbsp;yards and one touchdown as the Cardinals garnered 190&nbsp;yards rushing. Ball State had 487&nbsp;yards total offense. Davisâ two other touchdown passes were a 49&nbsp;yard completion to Dante Love and an eight yard pass to Darius Hill in the first half. He completed 21&nbsp;of 24&nbsp;passes with no interceptions. The Huskies were down 28â0&nbsp;with 50&nbsp;seconds left in the first half when Greg Abelli scored on a 20&nbsp;yard run. The Cardinals quickly responded with a 25&nbsp;yard field goal by Ian McGarvey to make it 31â7&nbsp;at halftime. Ball State lengthened its lead after the break to 48â7&nbsp;with a 27&nbsp;yard pass from Davis to Daniel Ifft, a Cory Sykes six yard run and another McGarvey field goal. Northeastern backup quarterback John Sperrazza, who completed six of seven passes for 82&nbsp;yards, threw a pass to Conor Gilmartin-Donohue for a 10&nbsp;yard touchdown with 38&nbsp;seconds left in the game. Starter Anthony Orio completed 14&nbsp;of 30&nbsp;passes for 149&nbsp;yards.<ref>{{cite news | agency =Associated Press | title =Ball St. beats Northeastern 48-14 | publisher =[[Rivals.com]] from [[Yahoo! Sports]] | date =2008-08-28 | url =http://rivals.yahoo.com/ncaa/football/news?slug=ap-northeastern-ballst&prov=ap&type=lgns | accessdate =2008-08-29 }}</ref>
===Navy=== {{Linescore Amfootball| |Road=Midshipmen |R1=6 |R2=10 |R3=7 |R4=0 |Home='''Cardinals''' |H1=14 |H2=7 |H3=7 |H4=7 }}
Nate Davis passed for 326&nbsp;yards and four touchdowns, but it was the Cardinalsâ defense that repeatedly came up with the big plays in the second half of a 35â23&nbsp;victory over the Midshipmen. Davis passed for 215&nbsp;yards in the first half, including touchdowns of 61&nbsp;yards to Dante Love on the second play of the game and 30&nbsp;yards to Briggs Orsbon late in the second quarter. Love, who tied a school record with his eleventh game of at least 100&nbsp;yards receiving, also rushed for a touchdown and caught a go-ahead 8&nbsp;yard touchdown pass from Davis midway through the third quarter. After Loveâs second touchdown catch put Ball State ahead 28â23, Navy threatened to take the lead again late in the third period. Shun White, who set a Navy rushing record with 348&nbsp;yards and three touchdowns in the previous week, was stopped at the 3&nbsp;yard line, and quarterback Jarod Bryant, who ran for Navyâs first two touchdowns, was held for no gain on fourth down, giving the ball back to the Cardinals. Ball State then put the game out of reach with a 97&nbsp;yard drive, scoring the clinching touchdown on a 35&nbsp;yard pass from Davis to Darius Hill early in the final period.<ref>{{cite web | last =Herman | first =Steve | title =Davis leads Ball State over Navy, 35-23 | publisher =Rivals.com from Yahoo! Sports | date =2008-09-05 | url =http://sports.yahoo.com/ncaaf/recap;_ylt=AtOfz7NPRnRcxJNRuYRzTRYcvrYF?gid=200809050048&prov=ap | accessdate =2008-09-06 }}</ref> The game was nationally televised on [[ESPN]] and earned a 1.2 [[Nielsen ratings|Nielsen rating]], making it the best regular season national television rating for a Mid-American Conference home game since 2005.<ref>{{cite web | title =Football Game vs. Navy Receives 1.2 Rating from ESPN | publisher =Ball State Athletics | date =2008-09-12 | url =http://ballstatesports.com/ViewArticle.dbml?SPSID=67657&SPID=7633&DB_OEM_ID=14200&ATCLID=1580449 | accessdate =2008-09-14 }}</ref> {{-}}
===Akron=== {{Linescore Amfootball| |Road='''Cardinals''' |R1=7 |R2=10 |R3=14 |R4=10 |Home=Zips |H1=3 |H2=7 |H3=0 |H4=14 }} MiQuale Lewis rushed for 154&nbsp;yards and two touchdowns and Nate Davis passed for 300&nbsp;yards and two more touchdowns to lead Ball State past Akron 41â24. Lewis carried 28&nbsp;times and scored on runs of three and two yards. Davis completed 24&nbsp;of 36&nbsp;passes with one interception, throwing touchdown passes of 21&nbsp;yards to Briggs Orsbon and 25&nbsp;yards to Darius Hill. Chris Jacquemain completed 21&nbsp;of 44&nbsp;passes for 269&nbsp;yards and a 13&nbsp;yard touchdown pass to Andre Jones, but was also intercepted off four times, three of them by Sean Baker. With the score tied at 10&nbsp;early in the second quarter, the Cardinals scored 21&nbsp;points on Lewisâ two touchdown and Bakerâs 33&nbsp;yard return of a fumble.<ref>{{cite news | agency =Associated Press | title =Ball St. 41, Akron 24 | publisher =Rivals.com from Yahoo! Sports | date =2008-09-13 | url =http://rivals.yahoo.com/ncaa/football/recap?gid=200809130047 | accessdate =2008-09-14 }}</ref> The victory marked the first time Ball State started the season 3â0 since 1988.<ref>{{cite web | title =Football Team Improves to 3-0 with 41-24 win at Akron | publisher =Ball State Athletics | date =2008-09-13 | url =http://ballstatesports.com/ViewArticle.dbml?SPSID=67657&SPID=7633&DB_OEM_ID=14200&ATCLID=1581470 | accessdate =2008-09-14 }}</ref> {{-}}
===Indiana=== {{see also|2008 Indiana Hoosiers football team}} {{Linescore Amfootball| |Road='''Cardinals''' |R1=14 |R2=14 |R3=0 |R4=14 |Home=Hoosiers |H1=6 |H2=14 |H3=0 |H4=0 }} MiQuale Lewis ran for 166&nbsp;yards and four touchdowns, helping Ball State to a 42â20 victory over Indiana. It was the first time the Cardinals beat a [[Bowl Championship Series|BCS]] conference school. The victory also ended Indiana's 20&nbsp;game winning streak against Mid-American Conference opponents, which dated to a September 24, 1977 loss against Miami (Ohio) when [[Lee Corso]] was coaching the Hoosiers. The Cardinals gained 463&nbsp;yards in offense, scored 28&nbsp;points in the first half and put the game away with two touchdown runs from Lewis in the fourth quarter. Indiana was led by Kellen Lewis, who ran for 148&nbsp;yards and one touchdown and threw for 159&nbsp;yards but was intercepted twice. Nate Davis was 16&nbsp;of 25&nbsp;for 239&nbsp;yards and threw one touchdown pass. Both teams combining for nearly 500&nbsp;total yards and two defensive touchdowns in the first half.<ref name="AP">{{cite news | last =Marot | first =Michael | title =Ball St. overcomes injury to upset Indiana 42-20 | agency =Associated Press | date =2008-09-21 | url =http://ap.google.com/article/ALeqM5jGYFrv1FkaOaOMHYq0k_sCLh2L0QD93AREF00 | accessdate =2008-09-23 }}</ref>
====Dante Love injury==== With 10:45 left in the first half, [[Dante Love]], who entered the game leading the nation at 144.3&nbsp;yards per game, caught a short pass and started to turn up field when Indiana cornerback Chris Adkins jarred the ball loose with a big hit that led to an Indiana touchdown.<ref name="AP"/><ref name="AP2">{{cite news | last =Marot | first =Michael | title =Injured Ball State WR Love likely out of football | agency =Associated Press | date =2008-09-22 | url =http://ap.google.com/article/ALeqM5j49-T4u1xc24LN4eM8ektapO80GAD93C0QI80 | accessdate =2008-09-23 }}</ref> Love stayed on the ground for several minutes before doctors rolled him onto a backboard and carted him off the field. School officials later issued a statement saying Love felt numbness and tingling while on the field. He was taken to Bloomington Hospital before being transferred to Methodist Hospital in Indianapolis for further evaluation.<ref name="AP"/> Love underwent a five hour surgery for a cervical spine fracture and a spinal cord injury and had movement in his arms and legs after the procedure.<ref name="AP2"/><ref>{{cite web | title =Ball State WR Love suffers career-ending injury | publisher =[[The Sports Network]] | date =2008-09-22 | url =http://www.sportsnetwork.com/merge/tsnform.aspx?c=sportsnetwork&page=cfoot/news/news.aspx?id=4181260 | accessdate =2008-09-23 }}</ref> On September 22, head coach Brady Hoke told reporters, "Due to the injury Dante sustained, his football career is expected to be over. He should have normal and healthy functions for the rest of his life. He touched a lot of lives, and he will continue to do so."<ref name="AP2"/>
