===Western Kentucky=== {{see also|2008 Western Kentucky Hilltoppers football team}} {{Linescore Amfootball| |Road='''Cardinals''' |R1=0 |R2=7 |R3=7 |R4=10 |Home=Hilltoppers |H1=0 |H2=0 |H3=0 |H4=7 }}
Nate Davis threw for 155&nbsp;yards and two touchdowns as Ball State overcame a slow start in its first ever game as a ranked team to beat Western Kentucky 24â7. Ball State led just 7â0 at halftime before eventually taking control in the third quarter. The Cardinals drove 64&nbsp;yards during the opening drive of the second half, though it ended with Ian McGarvey missing a 21&nbsp;yard field goal attempt. Afterwards, the Cardinals' defense forced Western Kentucky into a quick [[three and out]]. In the Cardinals' next offensive possession, Lewis ran up the middle of the field for 38&nbsp;yards to set up a one yard touchdown run that put the Cardinals up 14â0. McGarvey successfully kicked a 37&nbsp;yard field goal to push the lead to 17â0, and after Western Kentucky failed on fourth down deep in its own territory, Davis completed a pass to Louis Johnson for a 20&nbsp;yard touchdown with 6:31 remaining to put the game out of reach. The Hilltoppers garnered 352&nbsp;yards of offense but turned the ball over three times and fell to 0â5 against [[Football Bowl Subdivision]] teams in the season.<ref>{{cite news | last =Graves | first =Will | title =Ball St. remains undefeated with 24-7 win over WKU | agency =Associated Press | date =2008-10-11 | url =http://ap.google.com/article/ALeqM5gb_am7UtklecGANfFKSIOPSx4AQgD93OLV100 | accessdate =2008-10-12}}</ref> The Cardinals moved up one spot to #24&nbsp;in the Associated Press poll and entered the ''[[USA Today]]'' [[coaches poll]] at #25,<ref>{{cite web | title =Ball State football up one in AP and now ranked in coaches' poll | publisher =''[[The Star Press]]'' | date =2008-10-12 | url =http://www.thestarpress.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20081012/NEWS06/81012012 | accessdate =2008-10-13}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> The Cardinals were the first Mid-American Conference team to appear in the coaches poll since Bowling Green in 2004.<ref>{{cite web | title =Texas No. 1 in coaches poll after wild college football weekend | publisher =[[WKYC]] | date =2008-10-12 | url =http://www.wkyc.com/news/news_article.aspx?storyid=98438 | accessdate =2008-10-13}}</ref> During their bye week, the Ball State Cardinals moved from #24&nbsp;to #20&nbsp;in the Associated Press poll and from #25&nbsp;to #22&nbsp;in the ''USA Today'' coaches poll. Ball State also debuted at #20&nbsp;in the first BCS poll of the season.<ref>{{cite web | author =Star report | title =BSU football ranks No. 20 in 1st BCS poll | publisher =''[[Indianapolis Star]]'' | date =2008-10-19 | url =http://www.indystar.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20081019/SPORTS0603/81019014 | accessdate =2008-10-20}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref>
