===GMAC Bowl=== {{main|2009 GMAC Bowl}} {{see also|2008 Tulsa Golden Hurricane football team}} {{Linescore Amfootball| |Road=Cardinals |R1=7 |R2=6 |R3=0 |R4=0 |Home='''Golden Hurricane''' |H1=10 |H2=14 |H3=7 |H4=14 }}
Tulsa took the early 7â0&nbsp;lead over the Cardinals in the first quarter but Ball State answered back with an 18&nbsp;yard touchdown run from Nate Davis. The Cardinals defense held Tulsa to a 30&nbsp;yard field goal late in the first quarter but the Golden Hurricane went on to score with 10:39&nbsp;remaining in the second quarter increasing their lead to 17â7. Robert Eddins blocked the first punt of his career and Jeremy Hill recovered the ball to give Ball State favorable field position, which resulted in a 40&nbsp;yard field goal from Ian McGarvey with 6:36&nbsp;left in the second quarter and closed Tulsa's lead to 17â10. Tulsa made its way down the field quickly to go ahead of the Cardinals 24â10&nbsp;with 4:30&nbsp;left in the second quarter on a 57-yard touchdown run. With 29&nbsp;seconds before the completion of the first half, McGarvey made a 22&nbsp;yard field goal to close the gap to 24â13 at the break. During halftime, inclement weather conditions occurred with a heavy downpour which continued for the majority of the remainder of the game. But the weather did not hamper the Golden Hurricane who opened the second half with a touchdown to take a 31â13&nbsp;edge over Ball State. Tulsa added another touchdown after Tarrion Adams scored his third touchdown of the game making it 38â13&nbsp;with 13:29&nbsp;remaining in the fourth quarter. The last touchdown scored was with 10:25&nbsp;in the fourth when Tulsa completed a 13&nbsp;,yard pass to Jacob Frank making the score 45â13. The game marked the first time in school history Ball State has played in a bowl game in back-to-back season.<ref>{{cite web | title =Football Team Loses to Tulsa In GMAC Bowl | publisher =Ball State Athletics | date =2009-01-07 | url =http://ballstatesports.com/ViewArticle.dbml?SPSID=67657&SPID=7633&DB_OEM_ID=14200&ATCLID=3641468 | accessdate =2009-01-10}}</ref> With the loss, Ball State dropped out of the Associated Press and ''USA Today'' coaches poll.<ref>{{cite web | 